{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622599"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:03:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:03:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16807"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16807"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.3,0.22,0.27,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9498"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71111"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9498"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16807"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56582"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4938"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5207"},{"type":"tags","id":"5209"},{"type":"tags","id":"8512"},{"type":"tags","id":"10260"},{"type":"tags","id":"10315"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22898"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71111"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDepolarising neuromuscular blocking drugs are used in anaesthesia to facilitate endotracheal intubation and provide muscle relaxation during surgery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of depolarising neuromuscular blockers?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks acetylcholine release from motor neurones","Causes persistent activation of nicotinic receptors","Inhibits acetylcholinesterase at the neuromuscular junction","Competitively antagonises nicotinic receptors","Prevents acetylcholine synthesis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDepolarising neuromuscular blockers such as suxamethonium work through \u003Cstrong\u003Epersistent activation of nicotinic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E at the neuromuscular junction. This sustained depolarisation prevents the muscle from responding to subsequent nerve impulses, resulting in flaccid paralysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking acetylcholine release from motor neurones\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with botulinum toxin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting acetylcholinesterase\u003C/strong\u003E would increase acetylcholine levels and enhance rather than block neuromuscular transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompetitively antagonising nicotinic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of non-depolarising blockers like rocuronium rather than depolarising agents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreventing acetylcholine synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E would take too long to achieve clinical effect and is not how these drugs work.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe initial binding of the drug causes brief muscle fasciculations before paralysis occurs. This is a characteristic feature of depolarising neuromuscular blockade.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Depolarising neuromuscular blockers like suxamethonium work by persistently activating nicotinic acetylcholine receptors at the neuromuscular junction.","The prolonged depolarisation prevents muscle contraction and causes flaccid paralysis.","The initial receptor activation causes transient muscle fasciculations before paralysis occurs."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56582"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16807"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56582"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T06:57:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T06:58:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9498"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71111"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"em